The bmi attribute is complicated to understand just with numbers, lets try to group the values in order to know the weight status of the samples.¶

In order to calculate the weight status we are going to consider the following groups:

Underweight: BMI is less than 18.5. Normal: BMI is 18.5 to 24.9. Overweight: BMI is 25 to 29.9. Obese: BMI is 30 or more.

In [44]:
# We define the function that classifies the BMI in different weight status.
def get_weight_status(bmi):
    if bmi < 18.5:
        status = "Underweight"
    elif bmi < 25:
        status = "Normal"
    elif bmi < 30:
        status = "Overweight"
    else:
        status = "Obese"
    return status


# We generate a new attribute that indicates the weight status.
df['weight_status'] = df['bmi'].apply(get_weight_status)
df

In [62]:
#Insurance companies calculate the charges depending on the impact and probability yo happen of different risks. 
#That is why we can expect weight status to be an important fact. To verify this, we are going to see 
#the relationship between the charges and this weight status:
plt.figure(figsize=(16,9))
sns.boxplot( x=df["weight_status"], y=df["charges"]);
plt.title('Charges relation by Weight status')
plt.xlabel('Weight status')
plt.ylabel('Charges') 

plt.show()

As we expected, the weight status plays an important role when calculating the charges. we can clearly see the fact that the more unhealthy the person is the higher the charges are.¶

In [64]:
# We define the function that classifies ages.
def get_age_group(age):
    if age < 30:
        category = "Young"
    elif age < 60:
        category = "Adult"
    else:
        category = "Elder"
    return category

# We generate a new attribute that indicates the age group.
df['age_group'] = df['age'].apply(get_age_group)
df

Visualize the data¶

In [24]:
#Understanding how smoking affects the relationships between bmi and insurance charges
#We will use scatterplot to display the relationships between the three variables, one way to do is color coding the points.
#we will color code the points by smoker and plot the other two columns on the axes
plt.figure(figsize=(16,9))
plt.title('How smoking affects the relationships between bmi and insurance charges')
sns.scatterplot(x = df['bmi'], y = df['charges'], hue = df['smoker'])
Out[24]:
<AxesSubplot:title={'center':'How smoking affects the relationships between bmi and insurance charges'}, xlabel='bmi', ylabel='charges'>

The scatter plot shows that while nonsmokers to tend to pay slightly more with increasing BMI, smokers pay much more.¶

In [25]:
sns.lmplot(x="bmi", y="charges", hue="smoker", data=df, line_kws={'color': 'black'})
plt.title('Smoker Vs Non-Smoker')
Out[25]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Smoker Vs Non-Smoker')

In the figure above, we use the sns.lmplot command to add two regression lines, corresponding to smokers and nonsmokers. The regression line for smokers has a much steeper slope, relative to the line for nonsmokers indicating higher charges with increasing bmi.¶

In [26]:

Out[26]:
<AxesSubplot:title={'center':'Insurance charges among smokers vs non-smokers'}, xlabel='smoker', ylabel='charges'>

Above plot shows us that: the customers who pay the most are smokers; whereas the customers who pay the least are non-smokers.¶
